Waiyaki Way and the median strip of Mombasa Road have had vegetation cleared to pave the way for road expansion. KeNHA will partner with Kenya Forest Service in not only beautification of the road but also reinstatement of vegetation cover. As policy, more trees are planted to replace those cut. 

Owing to the design specifications, the pedestrian crossings on Mombasa Road have been pulled down to enable road construction works. However, they will be restored upon project completion. 

The expressway will be a breath of fresh air for motorists as it will unlock the full potential of the green city in the sun. The billions lost to traffic congestion will be diverted to other areas of the economy and increase the national GDP, which will push the country closer to fulfilling the sustainable goals towards infrastructure and sustainability. 



